This paper is about extractive document summarization using a deep neural network model. The paper focuses on the salience estimation of sentences in a document, which is a common problem in natural language processing and information retrieval. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.CL (Computation and Language), cs.IR (Information Retrieval), and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also proposes a novel contrastive training strategy, which is a popular technique in unsupervised learning and representation learning, suggesting that cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is also a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper uses attention-based neural networks, which are commonly used in computer vision and natural language processing, indicating that cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is another possible sub-category.
